text: When I was maybe 14 or 15, myself and a buddy broke into an old abandoned house located in the middle of this run down property in hopes of finding some old and valuable items we could sell like jewelry or art. Anyway, the entire home was just beat, there was nothing in there but the smell of death and these 2 naked dolls (much like the boy) sitting in one corner of a bedroom, some scary shit, so we decided 'let's get the fuck outta here' on the way out however, there was a mirror hanging on a wall by the hallway, and written on the mirror in what appeared to be blood was the words "just wait"... My friend Mac, came and saw the mirror after I did and on seeing it, he just went crazy and sped out of there jumping through a window, so I got scared too and ran... It's been 20 years now, but every now and again I wonder what might have happened had we waited..

text: I want to share a story, about two years ago i went to a house in bethesda maryland, i work in ceramic tile and i was there to do a small repair in one of the upstairs bathrooms, nothing major. Anyway upstairs in this room i went and i saw they had a human looking doll sitting in a chair, like an older woman. I was with the homeowner and he spoke to the doll and referred to her as his "mom". He said to her, "mom, he is here to repair the cracked tiles in the shower". It was so scary, i swear all the time i was there i kept looking over my shoulder wondering if she would get up or something, this movie reminded me of that. Apparently some people believe spirits of dead people can live in objects such as dolls.

text: Okay, so this movie wasn't scary at all. (There were little children in the theatre, but I wouldn't recommend that just in case.) The only jump scare was the one at the end of the trailer (so you expect it.) The characters were actually likable. I didn't want all of them to be killed like in most horror movies. And, there's a pretty decent plot twist. Honestly, this movie was so much better than I thought it'd be. I actually kind of want to see it again. I had low hopes for this movie, and thought it'd fail miserably like The Forest, but it blew up my low expectations. It really was worth my 8$ ticket. 7/10 would recommend.

Or was it a coincidence he got burned so they just used that as a chance?  -was there other nannies before Greta came into the picture? And if so did they all end up dead?  -And lastly, if the parents were so fed up with the 'real' Brahms, why didn't they ditch him a long time ago?  - And actually last one, you think Brahm's actually enjoyed watching Greta be nice to his doll version? It'd make more sense to me if he just interacted with her in person. Or is he just too socially fucked up? Lol anyways I know its just a movie but I wanted to see if anyone had answers to this confusing ass movie. Plus did you like it? Thanks.

I think that if you know the plot twist at the end while watching the movie, it makes it a whole lot more creepy because you know what is actually going on in the house. Before I left last night I read some of these comments to get a feel of how the movie was and like 10 people spoiled the ending. But I'm kind of glad they did. text: ****************Spoiler******************** For those of you who aren't going to watch it, yes its very strange especially the ending but its not far off from realistic. The doll isn't a demon but just a doll. The actually child who is supposed to be the doll is all grown up and is living in the basement of the house and he has ways of seeing through the walls and exiting and entering whenever to move the doll whenever no ones looking. In the beginning they do believe its a spirit but that changes when someone breaks the doll and the man child psychopath comes out of the walls to try and kill everyone. So basically that kid that "died" was still alive for 20 years manipulating the doll. He's just a crazy psychopath and there are people like that out there. At least it wasn't some corny demon like in most movies. I kind of thought it was a nice plot twist for a change.

Story in here is so bland and uninteresting, porculain doll was not intimidating, i laughed at certain parts when they tried to make him menacing. Scares are not there, it is just foolish dream sequences and loud effects. Characters make dumb choices all the time. text: I wonder if maybe someday in the distant future mankind will develop the technology to create horror films without the obligatory "young 'hot and sexy' woman gets naked in the shower or bath" garbage; you know, like maybe in some futuristic society we will advance so much as to enable horror movies completely devoid of this gratuitous, annoying, and completely unnecessary trope that at least 50% of audiences are really sick of having to stare at every time they want to see horror. That said, like a lot of other movies this one was full of annoying cliches, people just seem to think this one is less stupid because there was a twist at the end; it's like all it takes for people to think a movie was good is if there was a twist,no matter how shitty the rest of it was. Tbh, I expected the twist to be more clever. [[[SPOILERS AHEAD]]] I expected it to be that it turns out Malcolm was actually Brahms, that he'd been staying in the house the whole time and stalking Greta while acting like 'the gentle good guy.' I thought the 'Brahms' living in the walls who was making phone calls would turn out to be the girl whom Brahms had supposedly murdered in childhood, and that that's why that person wore a mask now (to conceal a woman's face). Otherwise it wouldn't make sense for a fully-grown man to speak in a child's voice on the phone and so on. I thought the person living in the walls would turn out to be 'good' despite being freaky and that she would save Greta when Malcolm would eventually attack her, or something like that.
